'''Plain dress''' is a religious practice in which people dress in clothes of traditional modest design, sturdy fabric, and conservative cut. It is used to show humility and to preserve communal separateness from the rest of the world. It is practiced by some [[Amish]], [[Apostolic Church|Apostolics]] {{Fact|date=April 2008}}, [[Schwarzenau Brethren|Brethren]], [[Hutterite|Hutterites]], [[Mennonite|Mennonites]], traditionalist Catholics, and [[Religious Society of Friends|Quakers]], among others.<ref>''Why Do They Dress That Way?'' Stephen Scott. Intercourse, PA: Good Books. (1997).</ref> [[Hasidic]] and [[Haredi]] [[Judaism|Jews]] also dress plainly, [[Rabbi|Rabbis]] in particular.

